 to whom he lost by a wide margin in 2006. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. He was a member of the [[Colorado House of Representatives]] and a co-owner of a pottery company in [[Cortez, Colorado]].\n\n==Early political career==\nA lifelong Republican, he became involved in the unsuccessful [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 1976|Reagan presidential campaign of 1976]] and was a delegate to the Republican Convention that year. He also assisted with local campaigns for Reagan in 1980 and 1984 across [[Montezuma County|Montezuma County, Colorado]] and the 3rd Congressional district and was Republican chairman of the 3rd Congressional district for eight years. He was a board member of [[Mesa Verde National Park]], [[Crow Canyon Archaeological Center]], and the advisory board of [[Pueblo Community College]].{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n==Colorado legislature==\n\n===2008 election===\nOn February 5, 2008, he announced his candidacy for the Colorado House seat representing District 58. The announcement came shortly after the incumbent, Ray Rose, announced he would retire in 2008. He had no opposition in the Republican primary,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rs.ezvotetally.com/Reserved.ReportViewerWebControl.axd?ReportSession=syj1hm55hso5ty55pcuhyprg&ControlID=a61fb386-685c-4a0c-a691-71334ad539d8&Culture=1033&UICulture=1033&ReportStack=1&OpType=ReportArea&Controller=ClientControllerdnn_ctr370_ViewRS2005_ReportViewer1&PageNumber=1&ZoomMode=Percent&ZoomPct=100&ReloadDocMap=true&EnableFindNext=False&LinkTarget=_top |title=Colorado Statewide Cumulative Report - 2008 Primary Election |accessdate=2008-11-08 |work=Colorado Secretary of State }}</ref> but faced Democratic candidate Noelle Hagan in the November 2008 general election. Hagan's candidacy was endorsed by the ''[[Denver Post]]''<ref>{{cite news |author=Editorial Board |title=Post's picks in Colorado's House of Representatives |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_10741559 |work=Denver Post |date=October 17, 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-09 }}</ref> and the ''Montrose Daily Press'',<ref>{{cite news |first=Wendy |last=Norris |author2=Bob Spencer  |title=State candidate endorsement watch |url=http://coloradoindependent.com/11911/state-candidate-endorsement-watch |work=Colorado Independent |date=November 3, 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-09 }}</ref> but Tipton won with 59 percent of the vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://coreports.ezvotetally.com/Reserved.ReportViewerWebControl.axd?ReportSession=jexpso55dlbays450fyzrmb4&ControlID=3a1b317069f040849b2b689d78addfc9&Culture=1033&UICulture=1033&ReportStack=1&OpType=ReportArea&Controller=dnn_ctr376_ViewRS2005_ReportViewer1&PageNumber=1&ZoomMode=Percent&ZoomPct=100&ReloadDocMap=true&SearchStartPage=0&LinkTarget=_top |title=Colorado Statewide Cumulative Report - 2008 General Election |accessdate=2008-12-04 |work=Colorado Secretary of State }}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nWith Representatives [[Laura Bradford]] and [[Frank McNulty (Colorado legislator)|Frank McNulty]], Tipton planned on re-introducing a version of [[Jessica's Law]] to establish minimum sentences for [[child sex offender]]s,<ref>{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Anderson |title=Jessica's Law bill gets state sponsors |url=http://www.postindependent.com/article/20081125/COMMUNITY_NEWS/811249962 |work=Grand Junction Free Press |date=November 24, 2008 |accessdate=January 27, 2014 }}</ref> sponsoring bills to create a full-time judge position in [[Montrose, Colorado|Montrose]]<ref>{{cite news|first=Joe |last=Hanel |title=Rep. Tipton's issues include roads, sexual assault, education |url=http://www.cortezjournal.com/Main.asp?SectionID=1&SubSectionID=1&ArticleID=3813 |work=Cortez Journal |date=December 24, 2008 |accessdate=2008-12-27 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728120701/http://www.cortezjournal.com/Main.asp?SectionID=1&SubSectionID=1&ArticleID=3813 |archivedate=July 28, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=K.C. |last=Mason |title=Budget Woes Will Handcuff Colorado Legislature |url=http://www.telluridewatch.com/pages/full_story?page_label=news&id=1253738-Budget-Woes-Will-Handcuff-Colorado-Legislature&widget=push&instance=secondary_stories_left_column&article-Budget-Woes-Will-Handcuff-Colorado-Legislature%20=&open=& |work=Telluride Watch |date=January 7, 2009 |accessdate=2009-01-10 }}</ref> and to simplify water rights filing.<ref>{{cite news |first=Reilly |last=Capps |title=Ahern may give it another go |url=http://www.telluridenews.com/articles/2009/01/12/news/doc496be8bcf23ab611488556.txt |work=Telluride Daily Planet |date=January 12, 2009 |accessdate=2009-02-04 }}</ref> The attempt to introduce a version of Jessica's Law was unsuccessful, it dying in committee.<ref>{{cite news |first=Reilly |last=Capps |title=Political accusations fly after Colorado's \"Jessica's Law\" dies|url=http://www.denverpost.com/ci_22670788/political-accusations-fly-after-colorados-jessicas-law-dies |work=Telluride The Denver Post |date=February 26, 2009 |accessdate=January 27, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nFor the 2009 legislative session, Tipton was named to seats on the House Agriculture, Livestock, and Natural Resources Committee and the House Local Government Committee.<ref>{{cite press release |title=House Republican Committee Assignments Announced |date=November 18, 2008 |publisher=Colorado House Democrats |url=http://www.coloradohousegop.com/?q=node/92 }}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2006\n{{main article|United States House of Representatives elections in Colorado, 2006#District 3}}\nHe unsuccessfully challenged the then, first term, [[Democratic Party (US)|Democratic]] U.S. congressman, [[John Salazar]].  Tipton lost 38% to 62% for Salazar.<ref>{{cite news | first = Gary | last = Harmon | title = Salazar-Tipton rematch a different contest | date = 2010-08-03 | url = http://www.gjsentinel.com/news/articles/salazartipson_rematch_a_differ | work = [[Grand Junction Daily Sentinel]] | accessdate = 2010-10-28}}</ref>\n\n;2010\n{{main article|United States House of Representatives elections in Colorado, 2010#District 3}}\nHe again challenged Democratic incumbent [[John Salazar]] in {{ushr|CO|3}}. [[Libertarian Party (US)|Libertarian]] Gregory Gilman and independent Jake Segrest were also on the ballot, with independents John W. Hargis, Sr. and James Fritz qualified as write-in candidates. He decided to retire from the [[Colorado House of Representatives]] to run for Congress in 2010, again challenging Salazar.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rollcall.com/news/40479-1.html?type=printer_friendly | title = Tipton Joins Race Against Salazar | author = Greg Giroux | publisher = Roll Call | date = 2009-11-09 | accessdate = 2009-11-25}}</ref> In the Republican primary, he defeated Bob McConnell 56% to 44%.<ref>{{cite news | first = Mike | last = Lawrence | title = Steamboat\u2019s McConnell defeated in District 3, Scott Tipton wins GOP congressional primary, goes on to face Rep. John Salazar | date = 2010-08-10 | url = http://www.steamboatpilot.com/news/2010/aug/10/tough-loss-steamboats-bob-mcconnell/ | work = [[Steamboat Pilot & Today|Steamboat Pilot]] | accessdate = 2010-10-28 | quote = With 70 percent of precincts reporting results Tuesday night, Tipton, a state representative from Cortez, had received 56 percent of votes across the 3rd Congressional District, compared with about 44 percent for McConnell. }}</ref> In the general election, he defeated Salazar 50.10% to 45.76%.\n\n;2012\n{{main article|United States House of Representatives elections in Colorado, 2012#District 3}}\nIn 2012, he was challenged by [[Sal Pace]], a [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic]] state representative from [[Pueblo, Colorado|Pueblo]]. His re-election campaign was aided by $1.3 million in advertising against Pace, funded by the [[Grover Norquist]] led, [[Americans for Tax Reform]].<ref>{{cite news|title=ATR Announces 1.3 Million Dollar Ad Buy in Colorado\u2019s 3rd Congressional District|url=http://www.atr.org/atr-announces-point-million-dollar-ad-a7247|accessdate=October 30, 2012|date=October 12, 2012}}</ref> SG Interests, an oil and gas company from Texas, that sought to drill in the Thompson Divide area, also campaigned against Pace.<ref>{{cite news|title=Driller starts super PAC to support Tipton|url=http://www.durangoherald.com/article/20121029/NEWS01/121029486/Driller-starts-super-PAC-to-support-Tipton--|accessdate=October 30, 2012|date=October 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\n;2014\n{{main article|United States House of Representatives elections in Colorado, 2014#District 3}}\nIn 2014, he was challenged by Democrat Abel Tapia, Libertarian Travis Mero and UNA candidate Tisha Cadia.  He won with 56.14% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|title=Colorado Secretary of State|url=http://www.sos.state.co.us/pubs/elections/Results/Abstract/2014/general/congress.html|accessdate=August 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nHe has signed [[Grover Norquist]]'s [[Taxpayer Protection Pledge]].<ref name =\"ATR\">{{cite web|title=The Taxpayer Protection Pledge Signers 112th Congressional List|url=http://s3.amazonaws.com/atrfiles/files/files/091411-federalpledgesigners.pdf|publisher=Americans for Tax Reform|accessdate=November 30, 2011}}</ref> He has also supported the [[The Path to Prosperity|Ryan Plan]], having twice voted for it.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.chieftain.com/news/local/tipton-defends-gop-approach/article_4a4ef9e0-6266-11e0-bbbd-001cc4c002e0.html | title = Tipton defends GOP approach | author = Peter Roper | publisher = Pueblo Chieftain | date = 2011-04-09 | accessdate = 2012-10-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 Tipton signed a pledge sponsored by [[Americans for Prosperity]] promising to vote against any Global Warming legislation that would raise taxes.<ref>http://americansforprosperity.org/files/Tipton_Scott.pdf</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Conservation, Energy, and Forestry|Subcommittee on Conservation, Energy, and Forestry]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Natural Resources|Committee on Natural Resources]]'''\n** [[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on National Parks, Forests and Public Lands|Subcommittee on National Parks, Forests and Public Lands]]\n** [[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Water and Power|Subcommittee on Water and Power]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Small Business|Committee on Small Business]]'''\n** [[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Agriculture, Energy and Trade|Subcommittee on Agriculture, Energy and Trade]], chairman\n** [[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Investigations, Oversight and Regulations|Subcommittee on Investigations, Oversight and Regulations]]\n'''Caucus Memberships'''\n*Congressional Cement Caucus\n\n===Legislation===\nTipton introduced the [[Water Rights Protection Act]] into the House on September 26, 2013. The bill would prevent federal agencies from requiring certain entities to relinquish their water rights to the United States in order to use [[public lands]].<ref>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3189 - CBO|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/44956|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=March 11, 2014}}</ref> Tipton said the bill was needed because it \"provides critical protection for water rights' holders from federal takings by ensuring that federal government agencies cannot extort private property rights through uneven-handed negotiations.\"<ref name=COtiptonbill>{{cite news|last=Hudson|first=Audrey|title=Tipton Bill Seeks to Stop Feds from Trampling Water Rights|url=http://thecoloradoobserver.com/2013/10/tipton-bill-seeks-to-stop-feds-from-trampling-water-rights/|accessdate=March 12, 2014|newspaper=The Colorado Observer|date=October 11, 2013}}</ref> Tipton argued that the bill \"prohibits federal agencies from pilfering water rights through the use of permits, leases, and other land management arrangements, for which it would otherwise have to pay just compensation under the 5th Amendment of the Constitution.\"<ref name=COtiptonbill/>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn 2011, it was reported that he spent over $7,000 on vendors that did business with his nephew's company.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/colo-rep-tipton-facing-second-ethics-issue | title = Colo. Rep. Tipton Facing Second Ethics Issue | publisher = TheDenverChannel.com | date = 2011-06-09 | accessdate = 2012-10-30}}</ref> Also in 2011, Tipton wrote an apology letter to the [[House Ethics Committee]] after it became known that his daughter was using his name in an effort to secure government contracts from other Congressional offices.  In 2012, he violated House rules when his office mistakenly used taxpayer resources to promote a campaign event.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.denverpost.com/politics/ci_20084097 | title = Rep. Tipton violates House rules in promoting campaign event | author = Allison Sherry | publisher = The Denver Post | date = 2012-03-02 | accessdate = 2012-10-30}}</ref>\n\nA [[super PAC]], funded by oil and gas driller SG Interests, is registered at the address of Tipton's campaign attorney and run by a law clerk in his office.  Although it is a violation of election laws for super PACs and a candidate's campaign to coordinate their activities, Tipton's attorney said: \"I have specifically put up Chinese walls to make sure Charlie (law clerk) is in no way involved with the Tipton campaign, and I'm in no way involved with the Colorado Future Fund.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.durangoherald.com/article/20121029/NEWS01/121029486/Driller-starts-super-PAC-to-support-Tipton-- | title = Driller starts super PAC to support Tipton | publisher = Durango Herald | date = 2012-10-29 | accessdate = 2012-10-30}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n\n